I remember the battles of my youth

the restless wanderer of the heath

the mighty Fingal , the praise of unhappy Moina
its lonely head : the moss whistled to the wind
the rank grass of the wall

name in the song of bards

the white-bosomed maids beheld them above like a grove ; they foresaw the death of their youths , and looked towards the sea with fear
Fingal ; go , Ullin , to the king of swords
that we are mighty in battle
HOW stately art thou , son of the sea !
soft the ringlets of thy hair ! — But this tree
soft the ringlets of thy hair ! — But this tree
— Ruddy is thy face of youth ! soft the ringlets of thy hair ! — But this tree may fall ; and his memory be forgot ! — The daughter of the stranger will be sad , and look to the rolling sea :
the feast of Fingal , Carthon , from the rolling sea ! partake the feast of the king , or lift the spear of war
Carthon , bard of the woody Morven
DOST thou speak to the feeble in arms
to darken my soul with the tales of those who fell ?
to my soul , against the children of my foes
the crowded pride of his soul
Fingal to his soul , meet , at once , the king
to battle , before the noble Carthon fell
the chief , the race of his native streams

the coming down of the king

thee ? — I feel the sun , OH Malvina
